  "topic_id": "T02.04",
  "topic_name": "Multiplication (Introduction and Tables)",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Multiplication is a quick way of adding the same number again and again. Instead of writing 4 + 4 + 4, we can write 3 × 4 = 12, which means 3 groups of 4. We can show multiplication using equal groups or arrays (rows and columns). The multiplication tables of 2, 3, 4, 5, and 10 help us find answers quickly. An important rule is that we can swap the numbers and the answer stays the same: 3 × 4 = 4 × 3. This is called the commutative property. Skip counting (2, 4, 6, 8 … or 5, 10, 15, 20 …) is the same as multiplying.",
    "rules": [
      "Multiplication means repeated addition of the same number.",
      "3 × 4 means 4 + 4 + 4 (three groups of four).",
      "Equal groups must have the same number of items in each group.",
      "An array shows objects in equal rows and columns; rows × columns = total.",
      "Memorise tables of 2, 3, 4, 5, and 10.",
      "Skip counting by a number is the same as multiplying by that number.",
      "Commutative property: a × b = b × a (swapping gives the same product).",
      "All products in this topic are at most 100."
    ]
  },
